#RandomforestRegressor
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Extracting the target variable (y) and features (X)
y = file['177(R2,24H,C)']  # Target column
X = file.drop(['164(R2,24H,T)'], axis=1) 

# Identifying numeric and categorical columns
numeric_features = X.select_dtypes(include=['int64']).columns
categorical_features = ['Geneid']  # Add more categorical columns if needed

# Creating transformers
numeric_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')),
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())
])

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('onehot', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))
])

# Creating the column transformer
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numeric_transformer, numeric_features),
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
    ])

# Creating the pipeline
pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor),
                             ('regressor', RandomForestRegressor())])

# Splitting the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Fitting the model on the training data
pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Making predictions on the test set
predictions = pipeline.predict(X_test)

# Calculate Mean Squared Error and R-squared for each target column
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, predictions)

print("Mean Squared Error:", mse)
print("R-squared:", r2)

R-squared: 0.9944131578133832

#LASSO regression
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso

# Creating the pipeline
lasso_pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor),
                                  ('regressor', Lasso())])

# Fitting the Lasso model on the training data
lasso_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Making predictions on the test set
lasso_predictions = lasso_pipeline.predict(X_test)

# Calculating Mean Squared Error and R-squared
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, lasso_predictions)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, lasso_predictions)

print("Mean Squared Error:", mse)
print("R-squared:", r2)

threshold = 0.5  # Adjust the threshold based on your problem
binary_predictions = (predictions > threshold).astype(int)
precision = precision_score(y_test, binary_predictions, average='micro')
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, binary_predictions)
from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, accuracy_score, recall_score, f1_score

#KMeans Clustering
# Selecting the number of clusters (k)
k = 4

# Instantiate KMeans
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)

# Fit the model to your numeric data
kmeans.fit(numeric_file)

# Accessing cluster labels for each data point
cluster_labels = kmeans.labels_

# Visualizing clusters (example with first two features)
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x=numeric_file.iloc[:, 0], y=numeric_file.iloc[:, 1], hue=cluster_labels, palette='viridis')

#Accuracy for Kmeans using calinski_harabasz_score
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import calinski_harabasz_score

# Assuming X is your feature matrix with some categorical columns
# Perform one-hot encoding
X_encoded = pd.get_dummies(X)

# Apply KMeans
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3)
labels = kmeans.fit_predict(X_encoded)

# Calculate Calinski-Harabasz Index

from scipy.stats import f_oneway

# Perform ANOVA
f_statistic, p_value = f_oneway(*[file['185(R1,3D,T)'][file['188(R1,3D,C)'] == group] for group in file['188(R1,3D,C)'].unique()])

# Visualize ANOVA results using box plots
